{"questionId":"22642","questionHtml":"<div class=\"qb-parent-stem\"><p>Let the function <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>h</mi><mo>(</mo><mi>x</mi><mo>)</mo></math> represent the height in centimetres of a cylindrical tin can with&nbsp;diameter <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>x</mi><mtext> cm</mtext></math>.</p>\n<p style=\"text-align:center;\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>h</mi><mfenced><mi>x</mi></mfenced><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mn>640</mn><msup><mi>x</mi><mn>2</mn></msup></mfrac><mo>+</mo><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>5</mn></math>&nbsp;for&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>4</mn><mo>≤</mo><mi>x</mi><mo>≤</mo><mn>14</mn></math>.</p></div>\n<div class=\"qb-parent-stem\"><p>The function <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msup><mi>h</mi><mrow><mo>−</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow></msup></math> is the inverse function of <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>h</mi></math>.</p></div>\n<div class=\"qb-leaf-prompt\"><p>Find <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msup><mi>h</mi><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow></msup><mfenced><mn>10</mn></mfenced></math>.</p></div>","markschemeHtml":"<p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>h</mi><mfenced><mi>x</mi></mfenced><mo>=</mo><mn>10</mn></math>&nbsp; <strong>OR</strong>&nbsp;&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msup><mi>h</mi><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow></msup><mfenced><mi>x</mi></mfenced><mo>=</mo><msqrt><mfrac><mn>640</mn><mrow><mi>x</mi><mo>-</mo><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>5</mn></mrow></mfrac></msqrt></math>&nbsp; <strong>OR</strong>&nbsp;&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msup><mi>h</mi><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow></msup><mfenced><mn>10</mn></mfenced><mo>=</mo><msqrt><mfrac><mn>640</mn><mrow><mn>10</mn><mo>-</mo><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>5</mn></mrow></mfrac></msqrt></math>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbs